# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancova
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In this equation, the DV, $y_{ij}$ is the jth observation under the ith categorical group; the CV, $x_{ij}$ is the *j*th observation of the covariate under the *i*th group.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Variables in the model that are derived from the observed data are $\mu$ (the grand mean) and ${\overline {x}}$ (the global mean for covariate x ).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The variables to be fitted are $\tau _{i}$ (the effect of the *i*th level of the categorical IV), B (the slope of the line) and $\epsilon _{ij}$ (the associated unobserved error term for the *j*th observation in the *i*th group).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Under this specification, the categorical treatment effects sum to zero $\left(\sum _{i}^{a}\tau _{i}=0\right).$ The standard assumptions of the linear regression model are also assumed to hold, as discussed below.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In an agricultural study, ANCOVA can be used to analyze the effect of different fertilizers ( $\tau _{i}$ ) on crop yield ( $y_{ij}$ ), while accounting for soil quality ( $x_{ij}$ ) as a covariate.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Soil quality, a continuous variable, influences crop yield and may vary across plots, potentially confounding the results.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The model adjusts yield measurements for soil quality differences and evaluates whether fertilizer types differ significantly.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In this setup, ANCOVA partitions the total variance in crop yield into variance explained by soil quality (covariate), variance explained by fertilizer type (categorical IV), and residual variance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] By adjusting for soil quality, ANCOVA provides a more precise estimate of the fertilizer effect on crop yield.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The constraint $\sum _{i}\tau _{i}=0$ ensures that the categorical variable's effects are centered around zero, allowing for meaningful interpretation of group differences.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] It is standard in ANOVA and ANCOVA with categorical variables.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] ANCOVA can be used to increase statistical power (the probability a significant difference is found between groups when one exists) by reducing the within-group error variance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In order to understand this, it is necessary to understand the test used to evaluate differences between groups, the F-test.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The *F*-test is computed by dividing the explained variance between groups (e.g., medical recovery differences) by the unexplained variance within the groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If this value is larger than a critical value, we conclude that there is a significant difference between groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Unexplained variance includes error variance (e.g., individual differences), as well as the influence of other factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Therefore, the influence of CVs is grouped in the denominator.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] When we control for the effect of CVs on the DV, we remove it from the denominator making *F* larger, thereby increasing our power to find a significant effect if one exists at all.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Another use of ANCOVA is to adjust for preexisting differences in nonequivalent (intact) groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] This controversial application aims at correcting for initial group differences (prior to group assignment) that exists on DV among several intact groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In this situation, participants cannot be made equal through random assignment, so CVs are used to adjust scores and make participants more similar than without the CV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] However, even with the use of covariates, there are no statistical techniques that can equate unequal groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Furthermore, the CV may be so intimately related to the categorical IV that removing the variance on the DV associated with the CV would remove considerable variance on the DV, rendering the results meaningless.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] There are several key assumptions that underlie the use of ANCOVA and affect interpretation of the results.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The standard linear regression assumptions hold; further we assume that the slope of the covariate is equal across all treatment groups (homogeneity of regression slopes).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The regression relationship between the dependent variable and concomitant variables must be linear.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The error is a random variable with conditional zero mean and equal variances for different treatment classes and observations.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] That is, the error covariance matrix is diagonal.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The error terms should be normally distributed $\epsilon _{ij}$ ~ $N(0,\sigma ^{2})$ .
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The slopes of the different regression lines should be equivalent, i.e., regression lines should be parallel among groups.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The fifth issue, concerning the homogeneity of different treatment regression slopes is particularly important in evaluating the appropriateness of ANCOVA model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Also note that we only need the error terms to be normally distributed.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In fact both the independent variable and the concomitant variables will not be normally distributed in most cases.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If a CV is highly related to another CV (at a correlation of 0.5 or more), then it will not adjust the DV over and above the other CV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] One or the other should be removed since they are statistically redundant.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Tested by Levene's test of equality of error variances.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] This is most important after adjustments have been made, but if you have it before adjustment you are likely to have it afterwards.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] To see if the CV significantly interacts with the categorical IV, run an ANCOVA model including both the IV and the CVxIV interaction term.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If the CVxIV interaction is significant, ANCOVA should not be performed.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Instead, Green & Salkind suggest assessing group differences on the DV at particular levels of the CV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Also consider using a moderated regression analysis, treating the CV and its interaction as another IV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Alternatively, one could use mediation analyses to determine if the CV accounts for the IV's effect on the DV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If the CV×IV interaction is not significant, rerun the ANCOVA without the CV×IV interaction term.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] In this analysis, you need to use the adjusted means and adjusted mean squared error.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] The adjusted means (also referred to as least squares means, LS means, estimated marginal means, or EMM) refer to the group means after controlling for the influence of the CV on the DV.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If there was a significant main effect, it means that there is a significant difference between the levels of one categorical IV, ignoring all other factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] To find exactly which levels are significantly different from one another, one can use the same follow-up tests as for the ANOVA.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] If there are two or more IVs, there may be a significant interaction, which means that the effect of one IV on the DV changes depending on the level of another factor.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] One can investigate the simple main effects using the same methods as in a factorial ANOVA.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] While the inclusion of a covariate into an ANOVA generally increases statistical power by accounting for some of the variance in the dependent variable and thus increasing the ratio of variance explained by the independent variables, adding a covariate into ANOVA also reduces the degrees of freedom.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-covariance] Accordingly, adding a covariate which accounts for very little variance in the dependent variable might actually reduce power.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA was developed by the statistician Ronald Fisher.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In its simplest form, it provides a statistical test of whether two or more population means are equal, and therefore generalizes the *t*-test beyond two means.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] While the analysis of variance reached fruition in the 20th century, antecedents extend centuries into the past according to Stigler.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] These include hypothesis testing, the partitioning of sums of squares, experimental techniques and the additive model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Laplace was performing hypothesis testing in the 1770s.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Around 1800, Laplace and Gauss developed the least-squares method for combining observations, which improved upon methods then used in astronomy and geodesy.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] It also initiated much study of the contributions to sums of squares.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Laplace knew how to estimate a variance from a residual (rather than a total) sum of squares.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] By 1827, Laplace was using least squares methods to address ANOVA problems regarding measurements of atmospheric tides.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Before 1800, astronomers had isolated observational errors resulting from reaction times (the "personal equation") and had developed methods of reducing the errors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The experimental methods used in the study of the personal equation were later accepted by the emerging field of psychology which developed strong (full factorial) experimental methods to which randomization and blinding were soon added.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] An eloquent non-mathematical explanation of the additive effects model was available in 1885.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Ronald Fisher introduced the term variance and proposed its formal analysis in a 1918 article on theoretical population genetics, *The Correlation Between Relatives on the Supposition of Mendelian Inheritance*.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] His first application of the analysis of variance to data analysis was published in 1921, *Studies in Crop Variation I*.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This divided the variation of a time series into components representing annual causes and slow deterioration.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Fisher's next piece, *Studies in Crop Variation II*, written with Winifred Mackenzie and published in 1923, studied the variation in yield across plots sown with different varieties and subjected to different fertiliser treatments.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Analysis of variance became widely known after being included in Fisher's 1925 book *Statistical Methods for Research Workers*.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Randomization models were developed by several researchers.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The first was published in Polish by Jerzy Neyman in 1923.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The analysis of variance can be used to describe otherwise complex relations among variables.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A dog show is not a random sampling of the breed: it is typically limited to dogs that are adult, pure-bred, and exemplary.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A histogram of dog weights from a show is likely to be rather complicated, like the yellow-orange distribution shown in the illustrations.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Suppose we wanted to predict the weight of a dog based on a certain set of characteristics of each dog.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] One way to do that is to *explain* the distribution of weights by dividing the dog population into groups based on those characteristics.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In the illustrations to the right, groups are identified as *X*1, *X*2, etc.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In the first illustration, the dogs are divided according to the product (interaction) of two binary groupings: young vs old, and short-haired vs long-haired (e.g., group 1 is young, short-haired dogs, group 2 is young, long-haired dogs, etc.).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Thus, this grouping fails to explain the variation in the overall distribution (yellow-orange).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] An attempt to explain the weight distribution by grouping dogs as *pet vs working breed* and *less athletic vs more athletic* would probably be somewhat more successful (fair fit).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The heaviest show dogs are likely to be big, strong, working breeds, while breeds kept as pets tend to be smaller and thus lighter.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] As shown by the second illustration, the distributions have variances that are considerably smaller than in the first case, and the means are more distinguishable.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, the significant overlap of distributions, for example, means that we cannot distinguish *X*1 and *X*2 reliably.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Grouping dogs according to a coin flip might produce distributions that look similar.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] An attempt to explain weight by breed is likely to produce a very good fit.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] All Chihuahuas are light and all St Bernards are heavy.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The difference in weights between Setters and Pointers does not justify separate breeds.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The analysis of variance provides the formal tools to justify these intuitive judgments.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A common use of the method is the analysis of experimental data or the development of models.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The method has some advantages over correlation: not all of the data must be numeric and one result of the method is a judgment in the confidence in an explanatory relationship.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] There are three classes of models used in the analysis of variance, and these are outlined here.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The fixed-effects model (class I) of analysis of variance applies to situations in which the experimenter applies one or more treatments to the subjects of the experiment to see whether the response variable values change.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This allows the experimenter to estimate the ranges of response variable values that the treatment would generate in the population as a whole.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Random-effects model (class II) is used when the treatments are not fixed.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This occurs when the various factor levels are sampled from a larger population.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Because the levels themselves are random variables, some assumptions and the method of contrasting the treatments (a multi-variable generalization of simple differences) differ from the fixed-effects model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A mixed-effects model (class III) contains experimental factors of both fixed and random-effects types, with appropriately different interpretations and analysis for the two types.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Teaching experiments could be performed by a college or university department to find a good introductory textbook, with each text considered a treatment.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The fixed-effects model would compare a list of candidate texts.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The random-effects model would determine whether important differences exist among a list of randomly selected texts.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The mixed-effects model would compare the (fixed) incumbent texts to randomly selected alternatives.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Defining fixed and random effects has proven elusive, with multiple competing definitions.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The analysis of variance has been studied from several approaches, the most common of which uses a linear model that relates the response to the treatments and blocks.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Note that the model is linear in parameters but may be nonlinear across factor levels.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Interpretation is easy when data is balanced across factors but much deeper understanding is needed for unbalanced data.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In a randomized controlled experiment, the treatments are randomly assigned to experimental units, following the experimental protocol.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This randomization is objective and declared before the experiment is carried out.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The objective random-assignment is used to test the significance of the null hypothesis, following the ideas of C.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This design-based analysis was discussed and developed by Francis J.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Anscombe at Rothamsted Experimental Station and by Oscar Kempthorne at Iowa State University.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Kempthorne and his students make an assumption of *unit treatment additivity*, which is discussed in the books of Kempthorne and David R.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The assumption of unit treatment additivity usually cannot be directly falsified, according to Cox and Kempthorne.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, many *consequences* of treatment-unit additivity can be falsified.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For a randomized experiment, the assumption of unit-treatment additivity *implies* that the variance is constant for all treatments.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Therefore, by contraposition, a necessary condition for unit-treatment additivity is that the variance is constant.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The use of unit treatment additivity and randomization is similar to the design-based inference that is standard in finite-population survey sampling.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Kempthorne uses the randomization-distribution and the assumption of *unit treatment additivity* to produce a *derived linear model*, very similar to the textbook model discussed previously.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The test statistics of this derived linear model are closely approximated by the test statistics of an appropriate normal linear model, according to approximation theorems and simulation studies.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For example, the randomization-based analysis results in a small but (strictly) negative correlation between the observations.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In the randomization-based analysis, there is *no assumption* of a *normal* distribution and certainly *no assumption* of *independence*.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] On the contrary, *the observations are dependent*!
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The randomization-based analysis has the disadvantage that its exposition involves tedious algebra and extensive time.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Since the randomization-based analysis is complicated and is closely approximated by the approach using a normal linear model, most teachers emphasize the normal linear model approach.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Few statisticians object to model-based analysis of balanced randomized experiments.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, when applied to data from non-randomized experiments or observational studies, model-based analysis lacks the warrant of randomization.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For observational data, the derivation of confidence intervals must use *subjective* models, as emphasized by Ronald Fisher and his followers.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In practice, the estimates of treatment-effects from observational studies generally are often inconsistent.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In practice, "statistical models" and observational data are useful for suggesting hypotheses that should be treated very cautiously by the public.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The normal-model based ANOVA analysis assumes the independence, normality, and homogeneity of variances of the residuals.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The randomization-based analysis assumes only the homogeneity of the variances of the residuals (as a consequence of unit-treatment additivity) and uses the randomization procedure of the experiment.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Both these analyses require homoscedasticity, as an assumption for the normal-model analysis and as a consequence of randomization and additivity for the randomization-based analysis.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, studies of processes that change variances rather than means (called dispersion effects) have been successfully conducted using ANOVA.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] There are *no* necessary assumptions for ANOVA in its full generality, but the *F*-test used for ANOVA hypothesis testing has assumptions and practical limitations which are of continuing interest.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Problems which do not satisfy the assumptions of ANOVA can often be transformed to satisfy the assumptions.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The property of unit-treatment additivity is not invariant under a "change of scale", so statisticians often use transformations to achieve unit-treatment additivity.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] If the response variable is expected to follow a parametric family of probability distributions, then the statistician may specify (in the protocol for the experiment or observational study) that the responses be transformed to stabilize the variance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Also, a statistician may specify that logarithmic transforms be applied to the responses which are believed to follow a multiplicative model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] According to Cauchy's functional equation theorem, the logarithm is the only continuous transformation that relates multiplication operations to addition operations over the real numbers.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA is used in the analysis of comparative experiments, those in which only the difference in outcomes is of interest.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The statistical significance of the experiment is determined by a ratio of two variances.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This ratio is independent of several possible alterations to the experimental observations: Adding a constant to all observations does not alter significance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Multiplying all observations by a constant does not alter significance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] So ANOVA statistical significance result is independent of constant bias and scaling errors as well as the units used in expressing observations.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In the era of mechanical calculation it was common to subtract a constant from all observations (when equivalent to dropping leading digits) to simplify data entry.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The calculations of ANOVA can be characterized as computing a number of means and variances, dividing two variances and comparing the ratio to a handbook value to determine statistical significance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Calculating a treatment effect is then trivial: "the effect of any treatment is estimated by taking the difference between the mean of the observations which receive the treatment and the general mean".
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA uses traditional standardized terminology.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA estimates 3 sample variances: a total variance based on all the observation deviations from the grand mean, an error variance based on all the observation deviations from their appropriate treatment means, and a treatment variance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The treatment variance is based on the deviations of treatment means from the grand mean, the result being multiplied by the number of observations in each treatment to account for the difference between the variance of observations and the variance of means.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The fundamental technique is a partitioning of the total sum of squares *SS* into components related to the effects used in the model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For example, the model for a simplified ANOVA with one type of treatment at different levels.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The number of degrees of freedom *DF* can be partitioned in a similar way: one of these components (that for error) specifies a chi-squared distribution which describes the associated sum of squares, while the same is true for "treatments" if there is no treatment effect.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The *F*-test is used for comparing the factors of the total deviation.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] where *MS* is mean square, I is the number of treatments and $n_{T}$ is the total number of cases to the *F*-distribution with $I-1$ being the numerator degrees of freedom and $n_{T}-I$ the denominator degrees of freedom.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Using the *F*-distribution is a natural candidate because the test statistic is the ratio of two scaled sums of squares each of which follows a scaled chi-squared distribution.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The expected value of F is $1+{n\sigma _{\text{Treatment}}^{2}}/{\sigma _{\text{Error}}^{2}}$ (where n is the treatment sample size) which is 1 for no treatment effect.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] As values of F increase above 1, the evidence is increasingly inconsistent with the null hypothesis.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Two apparent experimental methods of increasing F are increasing the sample size and reducing the error variance by tight experimental controls.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The ANOVA *F*-test is known to be nearly optimal in the sense of minimizing false negative errors for a fixed rate of false positive errors (i.e. maximizing power for a fixed significance level).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For example, to test the hypothesis that various medical treatments have exactly the same effect, the *F*-test's *p*-values closely approximate the permutation test's *p*-values: The approximation is particularly close when the design is balanced.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Such permutation tests characterize tests with maximum power against all alternative hypotheses, as observed by Rosenbaum.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The ANOVA *F*-test (of the null-hypothesis that all treatments have exactly the same effect) is recommended as a practical test, because of its robustness against many alternative distributions.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA consists of separable parts; partitioning sources of variance and hypothesis testing can be used individually.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA is used to support other statistical tools.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Regression is first used to fit more complex models to data, then ANOVA is used to compare models with the objective of selecting simple(r) models that adequately describe the data.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The simplest experiment suitable for ANOVA analysis is the completely randomized experiment with a single factor.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] More complex experiments with a single factor involve constraints on randomization and include completely randomized blocks and Latin squares (and variants: Graeco-Latin squares, etc.).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The more complex experiments share many of the complexities of multiple factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA generalizes to the study of the effects of multiple factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] When the experiment includes observations at all combinations of levels of each factor, it is termed factorial.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Factorial experiments are more efficient than a series of single factor experiments and the efficiency grows as the number of factors increases.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Consequently, factorial designs are heavily used.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The use of ANOVA to study the effects of multiple factors has a complication.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In a 3-way ANOVA with factors x, y and z, the ANOVA model includes terms for the main effects (x, y, z) and terms for interactions (xy, xz, yz, xyz).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The proliferation of interaction terms increases the risk that some hypothesis test will produce a false positive by chance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Fortunately, experience says that high order interactions are rare.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The ability to detect interactions is a major advantage of multiple factor ANOVA.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Testing one factor at a time hides interactions, but produces apparently inconsistent experimental results.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Caution is advised when encountering interactions; Test interaction terms first and expand the analysis beyond ANOVA if interactions are found.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Texts vary in their recommendations regarding the continuation of the ANOVA procedure after encountering an interaction.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Interactions complicate the interpretation of experimental data.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Neither the calculations of significance nor the estimated treatment effects can be taken at face value.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] "A significant interaction will often mask the significance of main effects." Graphical methods are recommended to enhance understanding.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A lengthy discussion of interactions is available in Cox (1958).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Some interactions can be removed (by transformations) while others cannot.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A variety of techniques are used with multiple factor ANOVA to reduce expense.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] One technique used in factorial designs is to minimize replication (possibly no replication with support of analytical trickery) and to combine groups when effects are found to be statistically (or practically) insignificant.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] An experiment with many insignificant factors may collapse into one with a few factors supported by many replications.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Some analysis is required in support of the *design* of the experiment while other analysis is performed after changes in the factors are formally found to produce statistically significant changes in the responses.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Because experimentation is iterative, the results of one experiment alter plans for following experiments.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In the design of an experiment, the number of experimental units is planned to satisfy the goals of the experiment.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Early experiments are often designed to provide mean-unbiased estimates of treatment effects and of experimental error.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Later experiments are often designed to test a hypothesis that a treatment effect has an important magnitude; in this case, the number of experimental units is chosen so that the experiment is within budget and has adequate power, among other goals.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Reporting sample size analysis is generally required in psychology.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] "Provide information on sample size and the process that led to sample size decisions." The analysis, which is written in the experimental protocol before the experiment is conducted, is examined in grant applications and administrative review boards.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Besides the power analysis, there are less formal methods for selecting the number of experimental units.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] These include graphical methods based on limiting the probability of false negative errors, graphical methods based on an expected variation increase (above the residuals) and methods based on achieving a desired confidence interval.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Power analysis is often applied in the context of ANOVA in order to assess the probability of successfully rejecting the null hypothesis if we assume a certain ANOVA design, effect size in the population, sample size and significance level.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Power analysis can assist in study design by determining what sample size would be required in order to have a reasonable chance of rejecting the null hypothesis when the alternative hypothesis is true.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Several standardized measures of effect have been proposed for ANOVA to summarize the strength of the association between a predictor(s) and the dependent variable or the overall standardized difference of the complete model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Standardized effect-size estimates facilitate comparison of findings across studies and disciplines.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, while standardized effect sizes are commonly used in much of the professional literature, a non-standardized measure of effect size that has immediately "meaningful" units may be preferable for reporting purposes.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Sometimes tests are conducted to determine whether the assumptions of ANOVA appear to be violated.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Residuals are examined or analyzed to confirm homoscedasticity and gross normality.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Residuals should have the appearance of (zero mean normal distribution) noise when plotted as a function of anything including time and modeled data values.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Trends hint at interactions among factors or among observations.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] A statistically significant effect in ANOVA is often followed by additional tests.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This can be done in order to assess which groups are different from which other groups or to test various other focused hypotheses.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Follow-up tests are often distinguished in terms of whether they are "planned" (a priori) or "post hoc." Planned tests are determined before looking at the data, and post hoc tests are conceived only after looking at the data (though the term "post hoc" is inconsistently used).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The follow-up tests may be "simple" pairwise comparisons of individual group means or may be "compound" comparisons (e.g., comparing the mean pooling across groups A, B and C to the mean of group D).
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Comparisons can also look at tests of trend, such as linear and quadratic relationships, when the independent variable involves ordered levels.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Often the follow-up tests incorporate a method of adjusting for the multiple comparisons problem.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Follow-up tests to identify which specific groups, variables, or factors have statistically different means include the Tukey's range test, and Duncan's new multiple range test.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In turn, these tests are often followed with a Compact Letter Display (CLD) methodology in order to render the output of the mentioned tests more transparent to a non-statistician audience.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Many statisticians base ANOVA on the design of the experiment, especially on the protocol that specifies the random assignment of treatments to subjects; the protocol's description of the assignment mechanism should include a specification of the structure of the treatments and of any blocking.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] It is also common to apply ANOVA to observational data using an appropriate statistical model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Balanced experiments (those with an equal sample size for each treatment) are relatively easy to interpret; unbalanced experiments offer more complexity.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For single-factor (one-way) ANOVA, the adjustment for unbalanced data is easy, but the unbalanced analysis lacks both robustness and power.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] For more complex designs the lack of balance leads to further complications.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] "The orthogonality property of main effects and interactions present in balanced data does not carry over to the unbalanced case.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] This means that the usual analysis of variance techniques do not apply.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA is (in part) a test of statistical significance.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The American Psychological Association (and many other organisations) holds the view that simply reporting statistical significance is insufficient and that reporting confidence bounds is preferred.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] ANOVA is considered to be a special case of linear regression which in turn is a special case of the general linear model.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] All consider the observations to be the sum of a model (fit) and a residual (error) to be minimized.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] The Kruskal-Wallis test and the Friedman test are nonparametric tests which do not rely on an assumption of normality.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Below we make clear the connection between multi-way ANOVA and linear regression.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Linearly re-order the data so that k -th observation is associated with a response $y_{k}$ and factors $Z_{k,b}$ where $b\in \{1,2,\ldots ,B\}$ denotes the different factors and B is the total number of factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In one-way ANOVA $B=1$ and in two-way ANOVA $B=2$ .
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Furthermore, we assume the b -th factor has $I_{b}$ levels, namely $\{1,2,\ldots ,I_{b}\}$ .
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Now, we can one-hot encode the factors into the ${\textstyle \sum _{b=1}^{B}I_{b}}$ dimensional vector $v_{k}$ .
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In order to obtain a fully general B -way interaction ANOVA we must also concatenate every additional interaction term in the vector $v_{k}$ and then add an intercept term.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] With this notation in place, we now have the exact connection with linear regression.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] We simply regress response $y_{k}$ against the vector $X_{k}$ .
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] However, there is a concern about identifiability.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] In order to overcome such issues we assume that the sum of the parameters within each set of interactions is equal to zero.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] From here, one can use *F*-statistics or other methods to determine the relevance of the individual factors.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] We can consider the 2-way interaction example where we assume that the first factor has 2 levels and the second factor has 3 levels.
[src:ancova/analysis-of-variance] Define $a_{i}=1$ if $Z_{k,1}=i$ and $b_{i}=1$ if $Z_{k,2}=i$ , i.e. a is the one-hot encoding of the first factor and b is the one-hot encoding of the second factor.
[src:ancova/confounding] In causal inference, **confounding** is a form of systematic error (or bias) that can distort estimates of causal effects in observational studies.
[src:ancova/confounding] A **confounder** is traditionally understood to be a variable that (1) independently predicts the outcome (or dependent variable), (2) is associated with the exposure (or independent variable), and (3) is not on the causal pathway between the exposure and the outcome.
[src:ancova/confounding] Failure to control for a confounder results in a spurious association between exposure and outcome.
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounding is a causal concept rather than a purely statistical one, and therefore cannot be fully described by correlations or associations alone.
[src:ancova/confounding] The presence of confounders helps explain why correlation does not imply causation, and why careful study design and analytical methods (such as randomization, statistical adjustment, or causal diagrams) are required to distinguish causal effects from spurious associations.
[src:ancova/confounding] Several notation systems and formal frameworks, such as causal directed acyclic graphs (DAGs), have been developed to represent and detect confounding, making it possible to identify when a variable must be controlled for in order to obtain an unbiased estimate of a causal effect.
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounders are threats to internal validity.
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounding is defined in terms of the data generating model.
[src:ancova/confounding] Let *X* be an exposure (or independent variable), and let *Y* be the outcome (or dependent variable).
[src:ancova/confounding] Traditionally, a variable *Z* was considered to confound the relationship between *X* and *Y* if *Z* (1) independently predicts *Y*, (2) is associated with *X*, and (3) is not on the causal pathway between *X* and *Y*.
[src:ancova/confounding] Not controlling for *Z* introduces a spurious relationship between *X* and *Y*.
[src:ancova/confounding] However, several developments in causal inference over the past decades have shown that this definition of confounding is inadequate.
[src:ancova/confounding] This is because there can be pre-exposure variables associated with the outcome that, when controlled for, introduce rather than eliminate bias.
[src:ancova/confounding] Modern causal inference therefore typically defines a confounder in terms of the *minimally sufficient adjustment set*.
[src:ancova/confounding] Formally, a set of variables *Z* is a *sufficient adjustment set* for the effect of *X* on *Y* if, conditional on *Z*, the potential outcomes are independent of *X*.
[src:ancova/confounding] I.e. after adjusting for *Z*, the exposed and unexposed groups are exchangeable with respect to the outcome.
[src:ancova/confounding] A *minimally sufficient adjustment set* is an adjustment set *Z* where every member of *Z* is required to control for confounding.
[src:ancova/confounding] Under this framework, a confounder is defined as a member of the minimally sufficient adjustment set.
[src:ancova/confounding] In the language of directed acyclic graphs, confounding corresponds to the presence of one or more open backdoor paths between *X* and *Y*.
[src:ancova/confounding] A set of variables *Z* is a sufficient adjustment set if conditioning on *Z* blocks all backdoor paths from *X* to *Y*.
[src:ancova/confounding] The set is minimally sufficient if no proper subset of *Z* satisfies this property.
[src:ancova/confounding] Removing any variable from a minimally sufficient set reopens at least one backdoor path.
[src:ancova/confounding] A trucking company compares the fuel economy of trucks from two manufacturers (“A” and “B”) by measuring miles per gallon over one month.
[src:ancova/confounding] They find that A trucks appear more fuel-efficient.
[src:ancova/confounding] However, A trucks are more often assigned highway routes while B trucks are more often assigned city routes.
[src:ancova/confounding] Here, truck make is the independent variable, MPG is the dependent variable, and route type (or proportion of city driving) is the confounder.
[src:ancova/confounding] Because route type affects MPG and the route type differs across truck make, it confounds the comparison.
[src:ancova/confounding] Thus the observed difference likely reflects highway vs. city driving rather than truck make.
[src:ancova/confounding] A scientist is studying the relationship between birth order (1st child, 2nd child, etc.) and the presence of Down syndrome in the child.
[src:ancova/confounding] In this scenario, maternal age is a confounding variable, as it influences both the independent variable (birth order), and the dependent variable (Down syndrome).
[src:ancova/confounding] A scientist is studying the relationship between smoking status (smoker vs. non-smoker) and the presence of lung disease.
[src:ancova/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet affect health regardless of smoking status (a smoker and non-smoker with similar alcohol use and diet may have similar health risks).
[src:ancova/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet are associated with smoking status (smokers are, on average, more likely to drink alcohol or have less healthy diets than non-smokers).
[src:ancova/confounding] Alcohol consumption and diet are not consequences of smoking itself (smoking does not necessarily cause higher alcohol intake or poor diet, even if they are correlated).
[src:ancova/confounding] In this scenario, alcohol consumption or diet is a confounding variable, because it influences both the independent variable (smoking status) and the dependent variable (health outcome).
[src:ancova/confounding] If these factors are not controlled, the observed association between smoking and lung disease may be partly or entirely due to differences in alcohol use or diet rather than smoking itself.
[src:ancova/confounding] Consider a researcher attempting to assess the effectiveness of drug *X*, from population data in which drug usage was a patient's choice.
[src:ancova/confounding] The data shows that gender (*Z*) influences a patient's choice of drug as well as their chances of recovery (*Y*).
[src:ancova/confounding] because the observational quantity contains information about the correlation between *X* and *Z*, and the interventional quantity does not (since *X* is not correlated with *Z* in a randomized experiment).
[src:ancova/confounding] It can be shown that, in cases where only observational data is available, an unbiased estimate of the desired quantity $P(y\mid {\text{do}}(x))$ , can be obtained by "adjusting" for all confounding factors, namely, conditioning on their various values and averaging the result.
[src:ancova/confounding] which gives an unbiased estimate for the causal effect of *X* on *Y*.
[src:ancova/confounding] The same adjustment formula works when there are multiple confounders except, in this case, the choice of a set *Z* of variables that would guarantee unbiased estimates must be done with caution.
[src:ancova/confounding] The criterion for a proper choice of variables is called the Back-Door and requires that the chosen set *Z* "blocks" (or intercepts) every path between *X* and *Y* that contains an arrow into X.
[src:ancova/confounding] Such sets are called "Back-Door admissible" and may include variables which are not common causes of *X* and *Y*, but merely proxies thereof.
[src:ancova/confounding] In this way the physician can predict the likely effect of administering the drug from observational studies in which the conditional probabilities appearing on the right-hand side of the equation can be estimated by regression.
[src:ancova/confounding] Contrary to common beliefs, adding covariates to the adjustment set *Z* can introduce bias.
[src:ancova/confounding] In general, confounding can be controlled by adjustment if and only if there is a set of observed covariates that satisfies the Back-Door condition.
[src:ancova/confounding] Moreover, if *Z* is such a set, then the adjustment formula of Eq.
[src:ancova/confounding] Pearl's do-calculus provides all possible conditions under which $P(y\mid {\text{do}}(x))$ can be estimated, not necessarily by adjustment.
[src:ancova/confounding] Greenland, Robins and Pearl note an early use of the term "confounding" in causal inference by John Stuart Mill in 1843.
[src:ancova/confounding] Fisher introduced the word "confounding" in his 1935 book "The Design of Experiments" to refer specifically to a consequence of blocking (i.e., partitioning) the set of treatment combinations in a factorial experiment, whereby certain interactions may be "confounded with blocks".
[src:ancova/confounding] This popularized the notion of confounding in statistics, although Fisher was concerned with the control of heterogeneity in experimental units, not with causal inference.
[src:ancova/confounding] According to Vandenbroucke (2004) it was Kish who used the word "confounding" in the sense of "incomparability" of two or more groups (e.g., exposed and unexposed) in an observational study.
[src:ancova/confounding] Formal conditions defining what makes certain groups "comparable" and others "incomparable" were later developed in epidemiology by Greenland and Robins (1986) using the counterfactual language of Neyman (1935) and Rubin (1974).
[src:ancova/confounding] These were later supplemented by graphical criteria such as the Back-Door condition (Pearl 1993; Greenland, Robins and Pearl 1999).
[src:ancova/confounding] Graphical criteria were shown to be formally equivalent to the counterfactual definition but more transparent to researchers relying on process models.
[src:ancova/confounding] In the case of risk assessments evaluating the magnitude and nature of risk to human health, it is important to control for confounding to isolate the effect of a particular hazard such as a food additive, pesticide, or new drug.
[src:ancova/confounding] For prospective studies, it is difficult to recruit and screen for volunteers with the same background (age, diet, education, geography, etc.), and in historical studies, there can be similar variability.
[src:ancova/confounding] Due to the inability to control for variability of volunteers and human studies, confounding is a particular challenge.
[src:ancova/confounding] For these reasons, experiments offer a way to avoid most forms of confounding.
[src:ancova/confounding] In some disciplines, confounding is categorized into different types.
[src:ancova/confounding] In epidemiology, one type is "confounding by indication", which relates to confounding from observational studies.
[src:ancova/confounding] Because prognostic factors may influence treatment decisions (and bias estimates of treatment effects), controlling for known prognostic factors may reduce this problem, but it is always possible that a forgotten or unknown factor was not included or that factors interact complexly.
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounding by indication has been described as the most important limitation of observational studies.
[src:ancova/confounding] Randomized trials are not affected by confounding by indication due to random assignment.
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounding variables may also be categorised according to their source.
[src:ancova/confounding] The choice of measurement instrument (operational confound), situational characteristics (procedural confound), or inter-individual differences (person confound).
[src:ancova/confounding] A reduction in the potential for the occurrence and effect of confounding factors can be obtained by increasing the types and numbers of comparisons performed in an analysis.
[src:ancova/confounding] If measures or manipulations of core constructs are confounded (i.e. operational or procedural confounds exist), subgroup analysis may not reveal problems in the analysis.
[src:ancova/confounding] Additionally, increasing the number of comparisons can create other problems (see multiple comparisons).
[src:ancova/confounding] Peer review is a process that can assist in reducing instances of confounding, either before study implementation or after analysis has occurred.
[src:ancova/confounding] Peer review relies on collective expertise within a discipline to identify potential weaknesses in study design and analysis, including ways in which results may depend on confounding.
[src:ancova/confounding] Similarly, replication can test for the robustness of findings from one study under alternative study conditions or alternative analyses (e.g., controlling for potential confounds not identified in the initial study).
[src:ancova/confounding] Confounding effects may be less likely to occur and act similarly at multiple times and locations.
[src:ancova/confounding] In selecting study sites, the environment can be characterized in detail at the study sites to ensure sites are ecologically similar and therefore less likely to have confounding variables.
[src:ancova/confounding] Lastly, the relationship between the environmental variables that possibly confound the analysis and the measured parameters can be studied.
[src:ancova/confounding] The information pertaining to environmental variables can then be used in site-specific models to identify residual variance that may be due to real effects.
[src:ancova/confounding] Ethical considerations: In double-blind and randomized controlled trials, participants are not aware that they are recipients of sham treatments and may be denied effective treatments.
[src:ancova/confounding] There is a possibility that patients only agree to invasive surgery (which carry real medical risks) under the understanding that they are receiving treatment.
[src:ancova/confounding] Although this is an ethical concern, it is not a complete account of the situation.
[src:ancova/confounding] For surgeries that are currently being performed regularly, but for which there is no concrete evidence of a genuine effect, there may be ethical issues to continue such surgeries.
[src:ancova/confounding] In such circumstances, many of people are exposed to the real risks of surgery yet these treatments may possibly offer no discernible benefit.
[src:ancova/confounding] Sham-surgery control is a method that may allow medical science to determine whether a surgical procedure is efficacious or not.
[src:ancova/confounding] Given that there are known risks associated with medical operations, it is questionably ethical to allow unverified surgeries to be conducted ad infinitum into the future.
[src:ancova/confounding] Concerns have been raised that confounding in medical research can product false null results due to decreasing exposure reliability and increasing sibling-correlations.
[src:ancova/confounding] Artifacts are variables that should have been systematically varied, either within or across studies, but that were accidentally held constant.
[src:ancova/confounding] Artifacts are thus threats to external validity.
[src:ancova/confounding] Artifacts are factors that covary with the treatment and the outcome.
[src:ancova/confounding] Campbell and Stanley identify several artifacts.
[src:ancova/confounding] The major threats to internal validity are history, maturation, testing, instrumentation, statistical regression, selection, experimental mortality, and selection-history interactions.
[src:ancova/confounding] One way to minimize the influence of artifacts is to use a pretest-posttest control group design.
[src:ancova/confounding] Within this design, "groups of people who are initially equivalent (at the pretest phase) are randomly assigned to receive the experimental treatment or a control condition and then assessed again after this differential experience (posttest phase)".
[src:ancova/confounding] Thus, any effects of artifacts are (ideally) equally distributed in participants in both the treatment and control conditions.
[src:ancova/covariate] A variable is considered **dependent** if it depends on (or is hypothesized to depend on) an **independent variable**.
[src:ancova/covariate] Dependent variables are the outcome of the test they depend on, by some law or rule (e.g., by a mathematical function).
[src:ancova/covariate] Independent variables, on the other hand, are not seen as depending on any other variable in the scope of the experiment in question.
[src:ancova/covariate] Rather, they are controlled by the experimenter.
[src:ancova/covariate] In mathematics, a function is a rule for taking an input (in the simplest case, a number or set of numbers) and providing an output (which may also be a number or set of numbers).
[src:ancova/covariate] A symbol that stands for an arbitrary input is called an **independent variable**, while a symbol that stands for an arbitrary output is called a **dependent variable**.
[src:ancova/covariate] The most common symbol for the input is *x*, and the most common symbol for the output is *y*; the function itself is commonly written *y* = *f*(*x*).
[src:ancova/covariate] It is possible to have multiple independent variables or multiple dependent variables.
[src:ancova/covariate] For instance, in multivariable calculus, one often encounters functions of the form *z* = *f*(*x*,*y*), where *z* is a dependent variable and *x* and *y* are independent variables.
[src:ancova/covariate] Functions with multiple outputs are often referred to as vector-valued functions.
[src:ancova/covariate] In mathematical modeling, the relationship between the set of dependent variables and set of independent variables is studied.
[src:ancova/covariate] In the simple stochastic linear model *y**i* = a + b*x**i* + *e**i* the term *y**i* is the ith value of the dependent variable and *x**i* is the ith value of the independent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] The term *e**i* is known as the "error" and contains the variability of the dependent variable not explained by the independent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] With multiple independent variables, the model is *y**i* = a + b*x**i*,1 + b*x**i*,2 + ... + b*x**i,n* + *e*i, where *n* is the number of independent variables.
[src:ancova/covariate] In statistics, more specifically in linear regression, a scatter plot of data is generated with X as the independent variable and Y as the dependent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] The simple linear regression model takes the form of *Y**i* = a + B*x**i* + *U**i*, for *i* = 1, 2, ... , *n*.
[src:ancova/covariate] In this case, *U**i*, ... ,*U**n* are independent random variables.
[src:ancova/covariate] This occurs when the measurements do not influence each other.
[src:ancova/covariate] Through propagation of independence, the independence of *U**i* implies independence of *Y**i*, even though each *Y**i* has a different expectation value.
[src:ancova/covariate] Each *U**i* has an expectation value of 0 and a variance of σ2.
[src:ancova/covariate] The line of best fit for the bivariate dataset takes the form *y* = *α* + *βx* and is called the regression line. α and β correspond to the intercept and slope, respectively.
[src:ancova/covariate] In an experiment, the variable manipulated by an experimenter is something that is proven to work, called an independent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] The dependent variable is the event expected to change when the independent variable is manipulated.
[src:ancova/covariate] In econometrics, the term "control variable" is usually used instead of "covariate".
[src:ancova/covariate] Depending on the context, a dependent variable is sometimes called a "response variable", "regressand", "criterion", "predicted variable", "measured variable", "explained variable", "experimental variable", "responding variable", "outcome variable", "output variable", "target" or "label".
[src:ancova/covariate] In economics endogenous variables are usually referencing the target.
[src:ancova/covariate] "Explanatory variable" is preferred by some authors over "independent variable" when the quantities treated as independent variables may not be statistically independent or independently manipulable by the researcher.
[src:ancova/covariate] If the independent variable is referred to as an "explanatory variable" then the term "response variable" is preferred by some authors for the dependent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] "Explained variable" is preferred by some authors over "dependent variable" when the quantities treated as "dependent variables" may not be statistically dependent.
[src:ancova/covariate] If the dependent variable is referred to as an "explained variable" then the term "predictor variable" is preferred by some authors for the independent variable.
[src:ancova/covariate] In data mining tools (for multivariate statistics and machine learning), the dependent variable is called **target variable** (or in some tools as *label attribute*), while an independent variable may be called a *regular variable* (or *feature variable*).
[src:ancova/covariate] A variable may be thought to alter the dependent or independent variables, but may not actually be the focus of the experiment.
[src:ancova/covariate] So that the variable will be kept constant or monitored to try to minimize its effect on the experiment.
[src:ancova/covariate] Such variables may be designated as either a "controlled variable", "control variable", or "fixed variable".
[src:ancova/covariate] Blocking variables or experimental variables are characteristics of the persons conducting the experiment which might influence how a person behaves.
[src:ancova/covariate] Gender, the presence of racial discrimination, language, or other factors may qualify as such variables.
[src:ancova/covariate] Situational variables are features of the environment in which the study or research was conducted, which have a bearing on the outcome of the experiment in a negative way.
[src:ancova/covariate] Included are the air temperature, level of activity, lighting, and time of day.
[src:ancova/covariate] In modelling, variability that is not covered by the independent variable is designated by $e_{I}$ and is known as the "residual", "side effect", "error", "unexplained share", "residual variable", "disturbance", or "tolerance".
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In statistics, **homogeneity** and its opposite, **heterogeneity**, arise in describing the properties of a dataset, or several datasets.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] They relate to the validity of the often convenient assumption that the statistical properties of any one part of an overall dataset are the same as any other part.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In meta-analysis, which combines data from any number of studies, homogeneity measures the differences or similarities between those studies' (see also study heterogeneity) estimates.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Homogeneity can be studied to several degrees of complexity.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] For example, considerations of homoscedasticity examine how much the variability of data-values changes throughout a dataset.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] However, questions of homogeneity apply to all aspects of statistical distributions, including the location parameter.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Thus, a more detailed study would examine changes to the whole of the marginal distribution.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] An intermediate-level study might move from looking at the variability to studying changes in the skewness.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In addition to these, questions of homogeneity also apply to the joint distributions.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The concept of homogeneity can be applied in many different ways.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] For certain types of statistical analysis, it is used to look for further properties that might need to be treated as varying within a dataset once some initial types of non-homogeneity have been dealt with.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In statistics, a sequence of random variables is homoscedastic (/ˌhoʊmoʊskəˈdæstɪk/) if all its random variables have the same finite variance; this is also known as homogeneity of variance.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The complementary notion is called heteroscedasticity, also known as heterogeneity of variance.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The term originates from the Ancient Greek σκεδάννυμι *skedánnymi*, 'to scatter'.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Assuming a variable is homoscedastic when in reality it is heteroscedastic (/ˌhɛtəroʊskəˈdæstɪk/) results in unbiased but inefficient point estimates and in biased estimates of standard errors, and may result in overestimating the goodness of fit as measured by the Pearson coefficient.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The existence of heteroscedasticity is a major concern in regression analysis and the analysis of variance, as it invalidates statistical tests of significance which assume that the modelling errors all have the same variance.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] While the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator is still unbiased in the presence of heteroscedasticity, it is inefficient and inference based on the assumption of homoskedasticity is misleading.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In that case, generalized least squares (GLS) was frequently used in the past.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Nowadays, standard practice in econometrics is to include heteroskedasticity-consistent standard errors instead of using GLS, as GLS can exhibit strong bias in small samples if the actual skedastic function is unknown.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Because heteroscedasticity concerns expectations of the second moment of the errors, its presence is referred to as misspecification of the second order.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The econometrician Robert Engle was awarded the 2003 Nobel Memorial Prize for Economics for his studies on regression analysis in the presence of heteroscedasticity, which led to his formulation of the autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (ARCH) modeling technique.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Differences in the typical values across the dataset might initially be dealt with by constructing a regression model using certain explanatory variables to relate variations in the typical value to known quantities.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] There should then be a later stage of analysis to examine whether the errors in the predictions from the regression behave in the same way across the dataset.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Thus, the question becomes one of the homogeneity of the distribution of the residuals, as the explanatory variables change.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] The initial stages in analyzing a time series may involve plotting values against time to examine the series' homogeneity in various ways: stability across time as opposed to a trend, stability of local fluctuations over time.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In hydrology, data series across a number of sites composed of annual values of the within-year annual maximum river flow are analysed.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] A common model is that the distributions of these values are the same for all sites apart from a simple scaling factor, so that the location and scale are linked in a simple way.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] There can then be questions of examining the homogeneity across sites of the distribution of the scaled values.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] In meteorology, weather datasets are acquired over many years of record, and, as part of this, measurements at certain stations may cease occasionally while, at around the same time, measurements may start at nearby locations.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] There are then questions as to whether, if the records are combined to form a single longer set of records, those records can be considered homogeneous over time.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] An example of homogeneity testing of wind speed and direction data can be found in Romanić *et al*., 2015.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Simple population surveys may assume that responses will be homogeneous across the whole population.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] Assessing the homogeneity of the population would involve examining whether the responses of certain identifiable subpopulations differ from those of others.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] For example, car owners may differ from non-car owners, or there may be differences between different age groups.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] A test for homogeneity, in the sense of exact equivalence of statistical distributions, can be based on an E-statistic.
[src:ancova/homogeneity-statistics] A location test tests the simpler hypothesis that distributions have the same location parameter.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Minimization of this function results in a set of normal equations, a set of simultaneous linear equations in the parameters, which are solved to yield the parameter estimators, ${\widehat {\beta }}_{0},{\widehat {\beta }}_{1}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] where ${\bar {x}}$ is the mean (average) of the x values and ${\bar {y}}$ is the mean of the y values.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] This is called the mean square error (MSE) of the regression.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The denominator is the sample size reduced by the number of model parameters estimated from the same data, $(n-p)$ for p regressors or $(n-p-1)$ if an intercept is used.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] In this case, $p=1$ so the denominator is $n-2$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Under the further assumption that the population error term is normally distributed, the researcher can use these estimated standard errors to create confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis tests about the population parameters.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] where $x_{ij}$ is the i -th observation on the j -th independent variable.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] If the first independent variable takes the value 1 for all i , $x_{i1}=1$ , then $\beta _{1}$ is called the regression intercept.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The least squares parameter estimates are obtained from p normal equations.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] where the $ij$ element of $\mathbf {X}$ is $x_{ij}$ , the i element of the column vector Y is $y_{i}$ , and the j element of ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ is ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ .
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:ancova/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
